WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.720
[Amit Varma]: How do we evaluate our precedents in prime ministers?

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:12.040
[Amit Varma]: Ideally, we should do so on the basis of their governance.

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:16.720
[Amit Varma]: But governance is complicated, the economy is complicated, policy is complicated, the

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:21.340
[Amit Varma]: state is a convoluted beast that moves in many directions at once, and disentangling

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:23.200
[Amit Varma]: all of these is hard.

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:26.680
[Amit Varma]: How much of what happened is down to the decisions of the person at the top.

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:31.040
[Amit Varma]: How many of those decisions were good or bad, regardless of the consequences?

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:32.540
[Amit Varma]: What are the counterfactuals?

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:33.920
[Amit Varma]: What are the counter-narratives?

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: In most cases, we can't tell.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.720
[Amit Varma]: So we instead judge our leaders based on our prior perceptions of them, the image we already

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:41.880
[Amit Varma]: have in our minds.

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:46.440
[Amit Varma]: We rationalize or condemn everything they do, regardless of what they actually do.

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Often, we judge them based on the ideological or political tribe we have already chosen.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes, though, a leader is either so bad or so good that even those blinkers are irrelevant.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:00.120
[Amit Varma]: I feel like that when I think of a man called P. V. Narasimha Rao.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:06.280
[Amit Varma]: Born 101 years ago on June 28, 1921, Narasimha Rao happened to be the compromise candidate

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:10.520
[Amit Varma]: when he became the Prime Minister of India in June 1991.

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: India was in the middle of an existential economic crisis.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Bold action was needed to get us out of it.

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:21.320
[Amit Varma]: We needed to go against every political current that had brought India to where it was.

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Narasimha Rao was a man of great learning, but India needed a man of great action.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:31.400
[Amit Varma]: He realized the gravity of the situation and used his political skills to bring about the

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:36.160
[Amit Varma]: famous reforms that lifted hundreds of millions of people out of poverty.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:38.480
[Amit Varma]: What he did for humanity is incalculable.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:42.560
[Amit Varma]: And yet, his achievements are today minimized and even mocked by his own party.

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: There's a haunting image of dogs nipping at his half-burned body on his funeral pyre after

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:48.440
[Amit Varma]: he died.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:53.400
[Amit Varma]: And that's a perfect metaphor for what this country has done to one of its tallest leaders.

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.360
[Amit Varma]: If it was not for P. V. Narasimha Rao, I may not have been recording this today.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And if you're Indian, you may not have been listening to it.

